+// readWritePin implements read-after-write consistency.
+//
+// Previously this used a fixed TTL: for a short window after a write the
+// account was served from the primary, and afterwards from the replica. That
+// is racy â€” if replication lag exceeds the TTL (or the row hasn't replicated
+// at all yet), a read after the window hits a stale replica and returns the
+// pre-deposit value (or no row).
+//
+// Instead we remember the exact balance the client last wrote. An account
+// stays "pinned" until the replica has actually caught up to (at least) that
+// value. While pinned, reads are served from the primary. Once the replica
+// is observed to be at-or-past the last written balance, the pin is cleared
+// and reads can safely use the replica again. This makes read-your-writes
+// correctness independent of any timing assumption.
